issue.title: Fix dynamic color escape response
issue.body:
The dynamic color escape response would answer to requests with
rgb:0/0/0 when the color was completely black, instead of properly
responding with double-digit hex colors. This has been changed so that
Alacritty now alwaysy properly responds with the same number of hex
digits for all colors.

The number of digits has also been changed from two to four digits per
color, since that is the more commonly used format.

Fixes #2543.

No garbage typed after start

I've bisected first wrong commit to 298608f88c463705cfd6ee47035c049dbb1d9fa0 (background detection)

^[]11;rgb:fbfb/f1f1/c7c7^G

^[]11;rgb:fb/f1/c7^G

issue.title: ANSI codes being printed to stdout when opening and closing neovim
issue.body:
Thanks for developing alacritty! It is a super neat project!

I'm having an issue that I think is alacritty specific.

I'm the author of [`taskwarrior-tui`](https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/). It is a terminal user interface for taskwarrior developed in Rust. My code works fine in all the other terminal emulators that I've tested. I believe this is a bug in alacritty although it could very well be a bug in my implementation. After experimenting endlessly, I've concluded that I should post here to see what you have to say. 

I'm using [`tui-rs`](github.com/fdehau/tui-rs) with the [`crossterm`](https://github.com/crossterm-rs/crossterm/) backend for the terminal user interface for `taskwarrior-tui`. As I understand it, `tui-rs` and `crossterm` use ANSI escape sequences to allow users to develop terminal user interfaces.

For making a user interface in the terminal, in `taskwarrior-tui` and for accepting user defined inputs, I have a thread that calls the `crossterm::event::poll(timeout)` and `crossterm::event::read()`.

https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/blob/f4da25d751cfb87796956df05d8e6e9a2ec60bf2/src/util.rs#L91-L92`

There's a feature of taskwarrior that lets you open the contents of a "task" in neovim and edit the task. This works fine when I call `task edit` in the command line. However, when using `taskwarrior-tui`, since it is listening for keyboard presses in an event loop, I think something is going wrong when neovim starts up / shuts down. Here's a gif showing what happens:

![](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/894255/107279315-ca5cba00-6a4e-11eb-8cf4-65a902a699fc.gif)

You'll notice there's a string of characters `/0000/0000` that are being entered automically into the user interface without the user typing anything. `taskwarrior-tui` is calling `event::read()` to read I believe the `stdin` where these characters are buffered after opening and closing neovim.

To elaborate further on what is happening: When a user presses the `e` key, [`taskwarrior-tui` pauses the event loop using a `AtomicBool`](https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/blob/f4da25d751cfb87796956df05d8e6e9a2ec60bf2/src/util.rs#L85-L88).
Next, `taskwarrior-tui` runs `task edit` as a subprocess.
When the user saves and quits neovim, the subprocess is complete and [`taskwarrior-tui` resumes the event loop](https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/blob/f4da25d751cfb87796956df05d8e6e9a2ec60bf2/src/app.rs#L1464-L1466).

However, after resuming the event loop to capture future user key presses, when `event::read()` is called it picks up a sequence of characters that seem like ANSI escape sequences for setting the background color in Alacritty (`/0000/0000`). This is interpreted by `taskwarrior-tui` as something the user types, which is obviously not the case.

I changed the background color in the alacritty config file to `#ffffff` and I was getting `/ffff/ffff` being printed automatically into the user interface.

Is this a bug with alacritty? Or is there something I can do to prevent these characters from appearing in the `stdin` / when I call `event::read()`? 

cc: @donbex

There's more information on this thread about everything that I've tried:

https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/issues/46

Adding `thread::sleep(250)` after pausing and resuming the event thread seems to decrease the number of times this happens for me but it still seems to be happening for @donbex.

I looked through other issues on this repo. The closest related issue was https://github.com/alacritty/alacritty/issues/2543 but I'm not sure it is entirely related.

I've attached additional information below. If you are interested to reproduce this bug, you can use this commit where I've removed the sleep functions:

https://github.com/kdheepak/taskwarrior-tui/commit/84054f22fe3e6ea1fc13552afc497d051d42b388

1) You'll need to install `taskwarrior`. 
2) Build `taskwarrior-tui` from source
3) Add a task (Hit `a` and type a task name and hit enter)
4) Hit `e`
5) Save and exit vim
6) Watch the filter field fill up with `0000/0000` if your background is black
7) Repeat steps 4-6 to reproduce bug if it doesn't occur the first time

### System

OS: Linux/macOS
Version: `alacritty --version` output
```
alacritty --version
alacritty 0.7.1 (a852eb8)
```
